Raw dev notes -- March 2026

A side project of mine has grown way beyond what I originally planned. It started as a
simple thing: I'm in dozens of messaging groups -- professional communities, neighborhood
stuff, news, tech discussions. Keeping up with all of them was impossible. I'd open the
app after a busy day and see 500+ unread messages across 30 groups. Most of it noise,
but buried in there are things I actually need to know about.

So I built a monitor. It watches all my groups and at the end of each day, generates an
AI-powered digest -- a concise summary of everything important that happened, organized by
topic. Powered by Gemini. That part worked great. Then scope creep kicked in.

Now it also:
- Ingests email newsletters via IMAP polling and includes them in the digest
- Filters online articles using the LLM as a relevance judge based on my interest profile
- Has separate digest pipelines for different content categories (tech, community, religious content)
- Auto-forwards the daily digest to relevant groups with randomized timing
- Respects schedule constraints -- it knows about holidays and off-hours
- Has a reminder system that persists across container restarts
- Sends push notifications when something critical happens (session loss, system failures)

But honestly, the operational side was HALF the project. Maybe more:
- It runs in Docker on my Windows desktop. Docker Desktop crashes occasionally and I had
  to build auto-detection and restart logic.
- Windows fights you on running 24/7 services -- sleep mode, Modern Standby, random updates.
  I built a whole keep-awake system just to stop the PC from sleeping.
- Built a watchdog with escalating recovery: restart container -> restart Docker -> alert me
- Catch-up logic was tricky -- when the system comes back from downtime, it needs to process
  missed messages without creating duplicates. I cleaned up over 2000 duplicate records
  from the early days before I got dedup right.
- Some messaging groups have permanently broken API responses. No fix available upstream.
  I just had to accept it and handle the errors gracefully.

Getting the digest quality right took many iterations. The LLM would either be too verbose
(defeating the purpose) or miss important things. I ended up with a system where the prompt
gets the group names and content categories as context, and I tell it to be as long as
needed but skip only truly redundant content.

It started as a weekend hack. Now it's the tool I check every morning before anything else.
It's like having a personal research assistant that reads everything I can't and tells me
what matters. I'm planning to migrate it to a Raspberry Pi so it doesn't depend on my
desktop being awake.

The imposter syndrome part: I showed this to a friend and they said 'you built a product.'
I don't know about that, but it's definitely the most complex system I've built on my own.
